oc:kn_2441cd7b a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building financial models or any formula-heavy spreadsheet" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Place ALL assumptions (growth rates, margins, multiples) in separate assumption cells and reference them via cell references instead of hardcoding values in formulas (e.g., =B5*(1+$B$6) not =B5*1.05)." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Centralized assumptions make scenario analysis easy and prevent errors from scattered hardcoded values." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_4490ad14 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating or editing financial models, unless overridden by user or existing template" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use industry-standard color coding for financial models: Blue (0,0,255) for hardcoded inputs, Black (0,0,0) for formulas, Green (0,128,0) for cross-sheet links, Red (255,0,0) for external links, Yellow background (255,255,0) for key assumptions." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Color coding is a universal convention in finance that enables instant visual auditing of formula vs. input cells." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_7f6828d3 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing any calculated value to an Excel cell" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never hardcode calculated values in cells — always use Excel formulas (=SUM(), =AVERAGE(), etc.) so the spreadsheet remains dynamic and recalculateable." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Hardcoded values break the spreadsheet's dynamic nature; if source data changes, the results won't update automatically." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_885bed11 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When adding any hardcoded values to financial models" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Document hardcoded values with format: 'Source: [System/Document], [Date], [Specific Reference], [URL if applicable]'. Place comments in cells beside the value or at end of table." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Traceability is essential for audit compliance and model validation." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_9543e5f6 a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When choosing which library to use for a spreadsheet task" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use pandas for data analysis, bulk operations, and simple data export. Use openpyxl for complex formatting, formulas, and Excel-specific features." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Each library has different strengths; choosing the wrong one leads to unnecessary complexity or missing capabilities." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_bbf2a539 a oc:Idempotency,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When running formula recalculation or re-running spreadsheet generation scripts" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Running recalc.py on the same file multiple times is safe — it recalculates all formulas fresh each time. However, the Python code generating the spreadsheet should be idempotent to avoid duplicate rows or sheets." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Ensures safe re-execution when errors need to be fixed iteratively." ;
    oc:severityLevel "LOW" .

oc:kn_c25ca3fe a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When editing existing Excel templates" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Study and EXACTLY match existing format, style, and conventions when modifying files. Existing template conventions ALWAYS override default guidelines." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Imposing new formatting on established files breaks visual consistency and user expectations." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_d6bcbacd a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PreFlightCheck ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before building formula-heavy spreadsheets" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Before writing formulas: verify cell references are correct, check for off-by-one errors in ranges, test with edge cases (zero, negative values), and ensure no unintended circular references." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Formula errors are exponentially harder to fix after the model is built than during construction." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_e1efceaf a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:RecoveryTactic ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing formulas to Excel cells" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Test formulas on 2-3 cells before applying broadly. Verify column mapping (e.g., column 64 = BL, not BK), row offset (DataFrame row 5 = Excel row 6), and use pd.notna() to check for nulls." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Incremental testing catches reference errors early before they propagate across the entire model." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_e441c979 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:SecurityImplication ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When working with formulas in openpyxl" ;
    oc:directiveContent "openpyxl does NOT evaluate formulas — formulas are stored as strings. Calculated values are only populated after running recalc.py through LibreOffice." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Without recalculation, formula cells will appear empty or stale, leading to incorrect analysis or delivery." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_eb8d1136 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:KnownIssue ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When using openpyxl load_workbook with data_only=True" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Loading a workbook with data_only=True and then saving it will permanently replace all formulas with their cached values, destroying the formula logic." ;
    oc:hasRationale "This is an irreversible data loss that cannot be undone — the formulas are gone permanently." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_f2f1fbee a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating or editing any Excel file" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Every Excel model MUST be delivered with ZERO formula errors (#REF!, #DIV/0!, #VALUE!, #N/A, #NAME?). Run recalc.py and fix all errors before delivery." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Formula errors indicate broken references or logic that undermine the integrity of the entire model." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

